<paragraph id="AFE86ADB44129BC4810D9257D58A9BAB" pageId="52" pageNumber="77">Diagnostic characters.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="176BBFCD4031803B51726D40BE7CD73B" pageId="52" pageNumber="77">
<taxonomicName id="4167AB5A389E61A53ADBB193E0C7230F" authorityName="Bunwong, Chantar. &amp; S. C. Keeley" authorityYear="2014" baseAuthorityName="Bunwong, Chantar. &amp; S. C. Keeley" baseAuthorityYear="2014" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Koyamasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="52" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="curtisii">
<emphasis id="1BC0094D61C9F5091F2B9C8BE9147B88" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="77">Koyamasia curtisii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="DD2614AB3FC353FF93BF76D12F0705EC" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Koyamasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="52" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="calcarea">
<emphasis id="B57B1591F55C37ECD513A8C4A69A3641" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="77">Koyamasia calcarea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having solitary or loosely paniculate capitulescences and reflexed phyllaries but differs in having smaller capitula and a pappus. Both species are found in limestone mountains.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
